Thinking about a physics debate with partner. If two cars are traveling and car A is going 5mph and car B is going 10mph, and there is distance between them (the slower car is behind), and both accelerate to 20mph, but the faster car B accelerates over a longer period of time and the slower car A accelerates over a very short amount of time, is it possibly for the slower Car A to overtake the faster car B, without Car A ever going faster than car B? Or if you graphed the distance between them in respect to how quickly they accelerate and how many mph they are traveling would it become an asymptote if Car A can never exceed car Bâ€™s speed?
OOPS! Studio! 2023-11-29 12:21 AM
Wait, if car A never exceeds car B's speed, then it will never catch up (edited)
12:22 AM
without Car A ever going faster than car B?
But if we remove this part, then yes it's definitely possible (edited)
12:24 AM
Say car A accelerates to 20mph in 1 second, and car B takes 8 months to pull off the same acceleration Car A will be going 20mph while car B is going 10mph. That's twice the speed. It will close the gap at 10mph so even if we say car A was an entire mile behind car B, it will still only take 6 minutes to catch up and then be ahead of car B forever. 8 months down the road when car B is finally going as fast as car A, it will be thousands of miles behind (edited)
12:24 AM
And never catch up
starðŸ’« 2023-11-29 12:28 AM
I know itâ€™s definitely possible over the entire graph if it can exceed 20mph. And I suppose the limitation on exceeding its speed can be removed during the time of their accelerating up to the cap of 20mph. I guess the hypothetical was whether the higher instantaneous speed or whatever during the acceleration period would be enough to close the gap without allowing the car to exceed the others speed in mph.
OOPS! Studio! 2023-11-29 12:29 AM
Well the answer is certainly no
12:29 AM
If the car that's behind can never exceed the speed of the car that's ahead, then it can never close the gap
12:30 AM
The gap will only close while the car that's lagging is going faster than the car that's leading. The gap will widen if the inverse is true. The gap will retain its size if they both go the exact same speed.
12:31 AM
So as long as the car that's behind is going 5mph and the one that's ahead is going 10mph, the gap will just keep growing and growing and growing by 5 miles every hour. If the car that's behind then accelerates super fast, but still never goes faster than the car that's ahead, then it will only make the gap temporarily widen slower
12:31 AM
It will not make progress towards closing the gap (edited)
starðŸ’« 2023-11-29 12:34 AM
So it would likely become an asymptote situation no matter how much greater the rate of acceleration wasâ€¦ car A with not exceed Car B at any point during acceleration. Unless it can temporarily move more quickly during the time it takes Car B to reach 20mph during the acceleration period.
OOPS! Studio! 2023-11-29 12:35 AM
I don't know what "asymptote" means, aha But yes. This really all boils down to "The only way the gap can close is if, at some point, car A is going faster than car B. If that never happens, the gap will never close. Not even slightly." (edited)

Just math - a good example is y=1/x X will approach 0 but never reach it since 0^2 is 0, and you cannot divide by zero. And Y will approach 0 also, 1, 1 2, 0.5 3, 0.33 4, 0.25 5, 0.2 As x increases incrementally, the y value decreases by less each time, but for whatever value, it'll decrease more and more without ever passing 0 (edited)
